article.headline: Orlando rallies to continue dominance over Houston

images.name: McGrady Tracy 020408 inline
images.caption: Orlando's Tracy McGrady splits the Houston defense of Oscar Torres, left, and Kenny Thomas. McGrady scored eight of his 22 points in the last five minutes.

article.linkText: Rockets able to slow down Magic for only so long
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- For 43 minutes, Houston did a great job of keeping the Orlando Magic from running. And then the Magic ran the Rockets right out of the T.D. Waterhouse Centre -- as usual. Tracy McGrady scored eight of his 22 points in the final 4:55 as the Magic beat Houston 83-74 Monday night. Troy Hudson scored 19 points, and his 3-pointer with 1:04 remaining capped a 16-1 run that sealed the Magic's 10th consecutive home victory over Houston. The Magic's victory, paired with Indiana's 111-99 defeat to Cleveland, dropped Orlando's magic number for clinching a playoff berth to one. Orlando can lock up a postseason berth with a victory at New York on Tuesday night. Orlando, despite posting its best defensive first quarter (12 points) and first half (29 points) of the season, never could put the Rockets away. Magic coach Doc Rivers pinned the blame on Houston's slowdown offense. "I bet they used 20 seconds on every shot attempt," Rivers said. "It's very difficult to make a run when a team plays like that. They wanted to play it slow, and they forced us into that game." With 4:55 to go, McGrady's long jumper tied the game at 67 and sparked Orlando's game-winning tear. Darrell Armstrong followed with five consecutive points, and McGrady hit three consecutive baskets before Hudson's 3-pointer. Until McGrady's outburst, he was low-key as a superstar can be. Through three quarters, he had eight points on 3-for-10 shooting. "Once they took the lead, I looked up at the clock and said, 'OK, I've got to take over,' " McGrady explained. Armstrong finished with 14 points and five assists. Like McGrady, he struggled, missing six of his first seven shots, before turning it on. "Those shots, I know I can make," said Armstrong, who had 12 points after halftime. "I've just got to start knocking them down earlier." Steve Francis' 29 points led the Rockets, who lost for the sixth time in seven games. Terence Morris added 11 points and 10 rebounds. Houston was without guard Cuttino Mobley, sidelined with the flu. The Rockets trailed by as many as 13 midway through the third quarter, but rallied to tie the game with 6:52 remaining. The Rockets outscored Orlando 24-11 over a 10:28 stretch, with Francis contributing eight points. Moochie Norris' flying layup tied it at 63, and the Rockets broke ahead moments later 67-65. "The second half was good for us," Francis said. "I thought we did a good job of trying to get everyone else the ball." In the first quarter, the Rockets were held to 5-for-18 shooting while committing nine turnovers. They went nearly nine minutes without a field goal, allowing Orlando to go on a 15-2 run for an 11-point lead. "We couldn't throw it in the ocean," Houston coach Rudy Tomjanovich. "We missed wide-open shots, with guys that normally make those kinds of shots." However, Houston scored 12 consecutive points in less than four minutes to tie the score at 22 with 9:03 remaining before halftime. Game notes
The Rockets have not won a regular-season game in Orlando since Dec. 22, 1991. ... Orlando forward Mike Miller, who reinjured his left ankle last Thursday, might be out until the weekend. There's a chance he could play against New Jersey on Thursday, but Rivers said a return Sunday against Philadelphia was more likely. Miller sprained his ankle March 8 and missed nine games. ... Houston center Kelvin Cato returned to action after missing a game with a sprained left wrist. He started and had eight points and six rebounds. ... Former Orlando guard Dennis Scott was in attendance, and received an ovation when he was shown on the replay board during a first-period timeout. Scott still owns the franchise record for 3-pointers made with 981.
